04212nam a22005895i 9780271092027DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710920277 a10.1515/97802710920272doi  a(DE-B1597)600770  a(OCoLC)1280943770  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360002bisacsh1 aStuckey, Mary E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDeplorable :bThe Worst Presidential Campaigns from Jefferson to Trump /cMary E. Stuckey. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Creating Citizenship in a Republic, 1800/1840/1852 -- t2 Looking Backward During the Nation’s Centennial, 1876 -- t3 Introducing the Politics of Fear to the Twentieth Century, 1924 -- t4 The Veneer of Civility: The Subtle Politics of Racism, 1968 -- t5 The Southern Strategy Goes Bipartisan, 1992 -- t6 It Doesn’t Get More Deplorable Than This, 2016 -- tAfterword: Or Maybe It Does—A Few Words About 2020 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPolitical campaigns in the United States, especially those for the presidency, can be nasty—very nasty. And while we would like to believe that the 2020 election was an aberration, insults, invective, and yes, even violence have characterized US electoral politics since the republic’s early days. By examining the political discourse around nine particularly deplorable elections, Mary E. Stuckey seeks to explain why. From the contest that pitted Thomas Jefferson against John Adams in 1800 through 2020’s vicious, chaotic matchup between Donald Trump and Joe Biden, Stuckey documents the cycle of despicable discourse in presidential campaigns. Looking beyond the character and the ideology of the candidates, Stuckey explores the broader political, economic, and cultural milieus in which each took place. In doing so, she reveals the conditions that exacerbate and enable our worst political instincts, producing discourses that incite factions, target members of the polity, encourage undemocratic policy, and actively work against the national democratic project.Keenly analytical and compulsively readable, Deplorable provides context for the 2016 and 2020 elections, revealing them as part of a cyclical—and perhaps downward-spiraling—pattern in American politics. Deplorable offers more than a comparison of the worst of our elections. It helps us understand these shameful and disappointing moments in our political history, leaving one important question: Can we avoid them in the future?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074510840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027109202740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271092027423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271092027/original  a978-3-11-074510-8  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK